# Atlas UI — Coding Conventions (LEGACY FALLBACK)
#
# NOTE: This is the legacy .cursorrules format. Atlas has migrated to scoped
# .mdc rules under .cursor/rules/. This file exists only for older Cursor
# versions that don't read .mdc files. If you're seeing this warning, update
# Cursor and the scoped rules will take over.

## General

- TypeScript strict mode in every file
- `const` by default; never `var`
- Named exports only (Atlas re-exports from a single barrel in `src/index.ts`)
- One component per file; filename matches the default export (PascalCase)
- Keep component files under 150 lines; split into subcomponents if longer
- Write JSDoc on every exported component and public function

## Components

- Accept a single `props` object typed with an explicit `interface`
- Forward `ref` with `React.forwardRef` on every interactive element
- Accept and merge a `className` prop using the `cn()` helper from `src/lib/cn.ts`
- Never use inline styles except for animation transforms
- Use semantic HTML — no `<div>` for buttons or links

## Hooks

- Prefer composition over configuration — many small hooks over one big one
- Custom hooks live in `src/hooks/` and are named `useXxx`
- No hook calls inside loops, conditionals, or nested functions

## Testing

- Colocate tests: `Button.tsx` + `Button.test.tsx`
- Colocate stories: `Button.tsx` + `Button.stories.tsx`
- Every component ships with at least one story and one test
- Tests use Vitest + React Testing Library
- Prefer `getByRole` over `getByTestId`

## Don't

- Don't use `any` — use `unknown` and narrow
- Don't install UI libraries beyond the ones already in package.json
- Don't write `React.FC` — use an explicit prop interface
- Don't export a component from both the barrel and a subpath
